      "quote": {
        "comment": {
          "id": "4450d76c-ff44-43b9-bfd1-f5aa59dc7b41",
          "created_at": "2025-10-29T21:33:28.316Z",
          "updated_at": "2025-10-30T01:26:32.590Z",
          "post_id": "96b1631e-d006-4411-8bc3-e6aed4401987",
          "user_id": 174014404,
          "body": "I threw that into Gemini and got this. Also asked it to explain the flies etc. \n\n\"I don’t think the market will fall down really hard—just a little dip. If that happens, it might be a good time to make some smart bets for the year. But until I’m sure the dip is real, I use special tools (like flies, ratios, and calendars) to protect myself in case things get bumpy in the short term\"\n\n\n🎯 Flies (Butterfly Spreads) Imagine you’re playing a game where you bet on how high someone will jump. You think they’ll land somewhere in the middle — not too low, not too high. So you place bets on three spots: low, middle, and high. You win the most if they land in the middle! That’s like a butterfly spread — it works best when the market stays near a certain price.\n🪢 Ratios (Ratio Spreads) This is like trading marbles with your friends. You give away more marbles than you get back, hoping the ones you keep become super valuable. In trading, you sell more options than you buy, betting that the market won’t move too wildly — but if it does, you’re ready to catch some action.\n📅 Calendar Spreads Think of this like planning two birthday parties — one this month and one next month. You expect the second party to be more exciting, so you bet on that one lasting longer. In trading, you buy one option for later and sell one for sooner, hoping the market gets more exciting over time.",
          "status": "published",
          "parent_id": null,
          "is_locked": false,
          "quote_id": "6c41d1d5-eb00-4f47-946d-e04f276121b6",
          "pub_moderation_status": null,
          "trust_and_safety_status": null,
          "media_uploads": null,
          "reaction_count": 1,
          "reply_count": 0,
          "max_reply_created_at": null,
          "threadMediaUploads": [],
          "mentions": null,
          "recent_commenters": [],
          "has_reacted": false,
          "reactions": {
            "folded_hands": 1
          },
          "muted": true,
          "reported_by_user": false,
          "raw_body": "I threw that into Gemini and got this. Also asked it to explain the flies etc. \n\n\"I don’t think the market will fall down really hard—just a little dip. If that happens, it might be a good time to make some smart bets for the year. But until I’m sure the dip is real, I use special tools (like flies, ratios, and calendars) to protect myself in case things get bumpy in the short term\"\n\n\n🎯 Flies (Butterfly Spreads) Imagine you’re playing a game where you bet on how high someone will jump. You think they’ll land somewhere in the middle — not too low, not too high. So you place bets on three spots: low, middle, and high. You win the most if they land in the middle! That’s like a butterfly spread — it works best when the market stays near a certain price.\n🪢 Ratios (Ratio Spreads) This is like trading marbles with your friends. You give away more marbles than you get back, hoping the ones you keep become super valuable. In trading, you sell more options than you buy, betting that the market won’t move too wildly — but if it does, you’re ready to catch some action.\n📅 Calendar Spreads Think of this like planning two birthday parties — one this month and one next month. You expect the second party to be more exciting, so you bet on that one lasting longer. In trading, you buy one option for later and sell one for sooner, hoping the market gets more exciting over time.",
          "user_pub_role": null,
          "most_recent_comment_created_at": null,
          "mediaAttachments": []
